   =20
      Hack the SEC
   =20
 =20
A good plot for, like, an insider-trading Hollywood thriller would be if th=
e villains hacked into the computers of the U.S. Securities and Exchange Co=
mmission. The SEC, after all, is maybe the world=E2=80=99s greatest reposit=
ory of material information about public companies. Companies are constantl=
y filing earnings releases, merger announcements, management changes, proxy=
 fights, all sorts of material news on the SEC=E2=80=99s Edgar=C2=A0system.=
 If you hacked into Edgar you could =E2=80=A6=C2=A0well, in a movie, I gues=
s you could delay every filing by like 10 minutes, to give you a chance to =
read and trade on it? In the real world most of this stuff gets announced a=
fter market hours, and anyway it mostly goes out on non-Edgar press wires t=
oo, so this probably wouldn=E2=80=99t work that well.=C2=A0You know what wo=
uld work, though? There are companies that provide software for public comp=
anies to use to make Edgar filings, to =E2=80=9CEdgarize=E2=80=9D their pre=
ss releases and other documents so that they comply with SEC formatting req=
uirements. These services frequently=C2=A0store companies=E2=80=99=C2=A0mat=
erial information for a while as it is being finalized, before it is filed =
and made public on Edgar.=C2=A0You could hack=C2=A0them:The Servicers provi=
de proprietary, cloud-based software platforms to facilitate public compani=
es=E2=80=99 filing of periodic and other reports with the SEC. The Servicer=
s=E2=80=99 public company clients=E2=80=99 filings include, among other thi=
ngs, Forms 8-K and related exhibits, which consist of press releases contai=
ning the public companies=E2=80=99 earnings announcements. The=C2=A0Service=
rs=E2=80=99 public company clients can use the Servicers=E2=80=99 software =
platforms to create, edit, and submit their filings to the SEC via the SEC=
=E2=80=99s EDGAR filing system. ...Typically, the Servicers=E2=80=99 public=
 company clients begin the filing process for an earnings announcement by l=
oading a draft earnings announcement onto the Servicer=E2=80=99s platform. =
Once loaded, the public company client can edit the draft earnings announce=
ment on the Servicer=E2=80=99s platform, before finalizing the earnings ann=
ouncement and releasing the final version to the public via a newswire, and=
 filing the announcement with the SEC as an attachment to a Form 8-K called=
 =E2=80=9CExhibit 99.1.=E2=80=9D There is generally a window of several hou=
rs or days between the time that the public company client uploads the pre-=
release earnings announcement onto the=C2=A0Servicer=E2=80=99s platform and=
 the time at which the client publicly disseminates the final earnings anno=
uncement through a newswire and the filing of the Form 8-K with the SEC.Tha=
t is from an SEC complaint accusing five Russians of hacking into two diffe=
rent (unnamed) companies that provide Edgarizing and filing services for pu=
blic companies. (Here is the SEC=E2=80=99s announcement; there are also fed=
eral criminal charges.)=C2=A0One of them, Ivan Yermakov, allegedly =E2=80=
=9Cserved as a Russian military intelligence officer in the Russian Federat=
ion=E2=80=99s Main Intelligence Directorate of the General Staff (=E2=80=98=
GRU=E2=80=99)=E2=80=9D and in 2018 was charged by federal prosecutors =E2=
=80=9Cfor his alleged roles in a hacking conspiracy involving gaining unaut=
horized access into the computers of U.S. persons and entities involved in =
the 2016 U.S. presidential election.=E2=80=9D In this caper, he allegedly h=
acked into the services=E2=80=99 computers, stole pre-release earnings anno=
uncements, and gave them to the other defendants to trade:If the pre-releas=
e earnings announcement indicated that the public company client=E2=80=99s =
stock=C2=A0price was likely to increase, then the Trader Defendants bought =
stock in the company or CFDs referencing the company. If the pre-release ea=
rnings announcement indicated that the public company client=E2=80=99s stoc=
k price was likely to decline, then the Trader Defendants sold short shares=
 of the company=E2=80=99s stock or sold CFDs referencing the company. =E2=
=80=A6The Trader Defendants used the information hacked and deceptively-obt=
ained from the Servicers=E2=80=99 systems by Yermakov to realize at least $=
82.5 million in illicit profits between February 2018 and August 2020.This =
was actually a bit less lucrative than a previous  big hacker-insider-tradi=
ng case, in which the hackers got into the=C2=A0news wires=C2=A0that publis=
h press releases, but I enjoy it more because it is a little closer to the =
ironic =E2=80=9Chacking the SEC itself=E2=80=9D scenario. There is a pipeli=
ne by which information moves from being secret to being public, and if you=
 can hack into that pipeline you=E2=80=99ll get a lot of good stuff.Pretty =
good stuff, anyway.=C2=A0That previous case led to a  delightful academic s=
tudy finding that knowing every company=E2=80=99s earnings in advance was u=
seful, but not=C2=A0that=C2=A0useful, because, despite the SEC=E2=80=99s ca=
sual discussion above, it=E2=80=99s not that easy to tell by reading an ear=
nings release whether it =E2=80=9Cindicated=C2=A0that the public company cl=
ient=E2=80=99s stock=C2=A0price was likely to increase=E2=80=9D or decline.=
 Often the news in an earnings release is priced in! Here, the SEC complain=
t has=C2=A0a few case studies =E2=80=9Cof the more than 500 instances of tr=
ading before earnings announcements on the basis of hacked information by t=
he Trader Defendants between at least February 2018 and August 2020=E2=80=
=9D; the traders made money in each of these cases. It=E2=80=99d be funnier=
 if the SEC included a case study where they read the press release, said =
=E2=80=9Cah a bottom-line earnings beat,=E2=80=9D bought stock, and then lo=
st money as it went down instead of up.=C2=A0
