</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A basic premise of Web3 is that every =
product is simultaneously an investment opportunity. If you sign up for=C2=
=A0a Web3 social network or chat room or trading venue or let=E2=80=99s-buy=
-the-Constitution <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/=
26123257.256657/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cudGhldmVyZ2UuY29tLzIyODIwNTYzL2NvbnN0aXR1dGl=
vbi1tZW1lLTQ3LW1pbGxpb24tY3J5cHRvLWNyb3dkZnVuZGluZy1ibG9ja2NoYWluLWV0aGVyZX=
VtLWNvbnN0aXR1dGlvbg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB82c5bc1e" itemprop=3D"StoryLi=
nk" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text=
-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color=
: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">lark</a>, y=
ou will get some of that project=E2=80=99s tokens, which will entitle you t=
o use the project=E2=80=99s app or exchange or=C2=A0Constitution, and which=
 will give you=C2=A0some notional say in the decentralized governance of th=
e project. Also the tokens will appreciate in value if the project takes of=
f and more people want to use it. It=E2=80=99s as if being an early user of=
 Facebook or Uber also automatically made you a=C2=A0<em>shareholder=C2=A0<=
/em>of Facebook or Uber, and when those services got huge you got rich.</p>=
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">At the Wall Street Journal this weekend, Chris=
toper Mims wrote about =E2=80=9C<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusin=
ess.com/click/26123257.256657/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cud3NqLmNvbS9hcnRpY2xlcy9qYWNrL=
WRvcnNleS1hbmQtdGhlLXVubGlrZWx5LXJldm9sdXRpb25hcmllcy13aG8td2FudC10by1yZWJv=
b3QtdGhlLWludGVybmV0LTExNjM5ODAzNjU0/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB437468b4" ite=
mprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"colo=
r: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; bor=
der-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #c=
cc;">Jack Dorsey and the Unlikely Revolutionaries Who Want to Reboot the In=
ternet</a>=E2=80=9D[1]:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">What if=
, to take but one example, users of social networks collectively owned them=
, or at least could vote on how they were run and what kind of speech they =
allowed? And what if similar questions could be asked of just about any tec=
h company whose primary product is software and services=E2=80=94whether fi=
nancial, cloud computing, or even entertainment-related? ...</p><p style=3D=
"margin: 16px 0;">The answers are taking the form of services and apps that=
 are the first outlines of what their creators hope will someday eat the in=
ternet completely: a distributed, democratically ruled =E2=80=9CWeb 3.0=E2=
=80=9D or =E2=80=9CWeb3=E2=80=9D that will rise like a phoenix of 1990s-era=
 Web 1.0-idealism from out of the ashes of the corporation-controlled Web 2=
.0 that all of us currently inhabit.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16=
px 0;">For instance:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">DeSo=E2=80=
=94which, confusingly, is simultaneously a not-for-profit foundation, a blo=
ckchain and a cryptocurrency token, but explicitly not a traditional for-pr=
ofit corporation=E2=80=94is in many ways typical of the form. The idea behi=
nd DeSo is that everyone should be able to create their own social media se=
rvice, but also that they could be interconnected in ways that, say, Facebo=
ok and Twitter would never be=E2=80=94including shared accounts and other s=
hared data.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CThe thesis behind DeSo=
 is that if you can mix money and social, you can create new ways for creat=
ors to monetize,=E2=80=9D says Nader Al-Naji, founder and head of the DeSo =
foundation. =E2=80=9CInstead of creators monetizing from ads, they can mone=
tize from DeSo coins.=E2=80=9D</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">DeSo has cre=
ated a new cryptocurrency (named DeSo) that, for example, could be used to =
=E2=80=9Ctip=E2=80=9D other users for their posts, replacing likes with act=
ual money=E2=80=94or at least DeSo tokens that can be traded for dollars on=
 the usual cryptocurrency exchanges. Like other next-generation cryptocurre=
ncies, inspired by Ethereum, these tokens also can store the data that actu=
ally makes up a social network, such as the text of posts=C2=A0.... This du=
al function illustrates the inspired weirdness that is Web3: If money can b=
ecome code, then money can be way more than a means of exchange; it can als=
o do anything that other software can do.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">T=
his core insight, a sort of E =3D mc=C2=B2 equivalence between money and so=
ftware, is why true believers in Web3 think it could have such a huge impac=
t. Suddenly every activity humans engage in, from buying and selling a hous=
e to liking a post on social media, can be made part of a token-based finan=
cial system of a scale and complexity that makes today=E2=80=99s look like =
an antique.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I feel like the re=
ally interesting financial innovation of Web3 is its pyramid-scheme-like na=
ture. All sorts of things =E2=80=94=C2=A0social networks, financial exchang=
es, ride-sharing apps, decentralized file storage =E2=80=94=C2=A0benefit fr=
om network effects.[2] You log into Facebook because your friends are there=
, and they=E2=80=99re there because you=E2=80=99re there. You call an Uber =
because lots of drivers are on Uber, and the drivers use Uber because the p=
assengers do too. You might prefer the=C2=A0user interface of some niche so=
cial network or ride-sharing app, but if no one else uses it you won=E2=80=
=99t either. Some niche social network might say =E2=80=9Chey use our netwo=
rk and you can, like, vote on our content moderation policies or whatever,=
=E2=80=9D and you might find that attractive (why?), but it=E2=80=99s not a=
s attractive as Facebook=E2=80=99s promise that your friends are there.</p>=
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This network-effect dynamic=C2=A0favors big in=
cumbents: The big existing networks have better networks than small upstart=
s. If you are looking for a social network you will probably end up on a bi=
g popular one, not a small new one. Not always =E2=80=94=C2=A0Uber and Face=
book are pretty new companies, in the scheme of things; disruption is possi=
ble =E2=80=94=C2=A0but the incumbents have advantages.</p><p style=3D"margi=
n: 16px 0;">But in Web3 the economics are almost reversed. If you were an e=
arly user of Bitcoin now you=E2=80=99re a billionaire. If you=E2=80=99re an=
 early user of some Web3 social network, you will probably accumulate some =
of its tokens, and if it takes off you=E2=80=99ll get rich. This gives you =
an incentive to join the next thing, because being early to the next thing =
will make you rich, while joining the existing popular thing won=E2=80=99t.=
=C2=A0As I <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/2612325=
7.256657/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMT=
EtMDIvc3RhYmxlY29pbnMtbWlnaHQtaGF2ZS10by1iZS1iYW5rcz9jbXBpZD1CQkQxMjIxMjFfT=
U9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVy=
bT0yMTEyMjEmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB1f0ae7=
6f" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=
=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-c=
olor: #ccc;"> wrote last month</a>:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px=
 0;">When corporations fund projects, they hope to make money, so they fund=
 projects that they think people will like. When users fund projects, hopin=
g to get rich, the incentive to use the project is not just =E2=80=9Cthis i=
s a useful thing for me=E2=80=9D but also =E2=80=9Cif I use it I=E2=80=99ll=
 get rich.=E2=80=9D It turns, like, file-storage systems into also Ponzi sc=
hemes: The community of users is also a community of speculators.=C2=A0</p>=
</blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">People who like Web3 mostly think=
 this is good. <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/261=
